@node main "JustName Documentation - Contents"
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
                                JustName v1.02
              
              A very fast and flexible file renamer for the Amiga.
                     @{fg shine}Copyright © 2001-2010 Jostein Aarbakk@{fg text}
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------         

   @{" Introduction      " link Introduction}   What is JustName?
   @{" Features          " link Features    }   What can JustName do?
   @{" Requirements      " link Requirements}   Which systems will JustName run on?

   @{" Installation      " link Installation}   Before using JustName
   @{" Usage             " link Usage       }   How to use JustName
   @{" Tips & Hints      " link Tips        }   Some useful notes

   @{" History           " link History     }   History list
   @{" Technical info    " link Technical   }   Technical info
   @{" Disclaimer        " link Disclaimer  }   Short: Use it at your own risk
   @{" Author            " link Author      }   Where you can reach me
@endnode

@node Introduction "JustName Documentation - Introduction"
@{b}
Introduction
------------@{ub}

    JustName is a CLI based utility to mass-rename files.
    F.ex. change letters from lowercase to uppercase, replace substrings, add substrings, etc.
    The more files you need to rename at the same time, the more useful it gets.
@endnode
  

@node Features "JustName Documentation - Features"
@{b}
Features
--------@{ub}

    @{b}* Convert letters to uppercase or lowercase.@{ub}


    @{b}* Misc. "uppercase options":@{ub}
        * Make 1st. letter uppercase.
        * Make 1st. letter after a character uppercase
          (the user can specify one or more such characters).
        * Make roman numerals uppercase (ex: xvIi -> XVII).


    @{b}* Add/remove leading zeros in numbers.@{ub}


    @{b}* Remove CTRL-characters.@{ub}
      These are characters which are displayed
      as strange and meaningless characters, like f.ex squares.


    @{b}* Flexible filters:@{ub}
        * Wildcards are supported.
        * Perform actions on the prefix, main or suffix part of the filename.
        * Perform actions on selected substrings.
        * Perform actions before or after a substring.
        * Case sensitive or case insensitive pattern matching.


    @{b}* Replace filenames (or parts of it, if a filter is used) with:@{ub}
        * a given string, or
        * the contents of the file's filenote.


    @{b}* Insert new text:@{ub}
       * At the start or after the end.
       * Before or after a selected part of the filename.


    @{b}* Flexible file selection:@{ub}
        * Filenames can be up to 108 characters long.
        * You can choose as many files as you like.
        * Wildcards.


    @{b}* Most of the features above can be combined together.


    @{b}* Can perform multiple actions on filenames in one go (&&-option):@{ub}
      This makes it possible to do several different renaming operations in one go
      which otherwise had to be done via several calls to JustName.
      Each file will only be written to disk once.


    @{b}* Very efficient processing:@{ub}
        * Optimized. It won't do any unnecessary work.
        * Has an option ("o") which makes JustName execute faster when 
          using a filemanager like f.ex. Directory Opus.
@endnode


@node Requirements "JustName Documentation - Requirements"
@{b}
Requirements
------------@{ub}
    
    It will work on:
    * Any Classic Amiga with at least a 68000 processor, and at least Kickstart 1.2.
    * Any Amiga with OS4.1 (via JIT emulation). The speed is remarkably fast here too!


    It has been tested on classic amigas:
    
       1) from CLI and Directory Opus 4 on Amigas using standard filesystem:
          * A500  / 0.5MB Fast / Kickstart 1.3
          * A1200 / Blizzard 1230 / 32MB Fast / Kickstart 3.1 / 40GB HD
 
       2) with Directory Opus 5 using standard filesystem:
          * A1200 / Blizzard 1230 / 32MB Fast / Kickstart 3.1 / 40GB HD    


    ...and a PPC-equipped Amiga with OS4.1:
 
       1) from CLI and Directory Opus 4 on Amiga using OFS/SFS00/SFS02/JXSF filesystems:
          * Sam440EP / 512MB / OS4.1 / 30GB OCZ Solid State Drive
@endnode


@node Usage "JustName Documentation - Usage"
@{b}
Usage
-----@{ub}

    @{fg text}@{b}JustName@{ub} [-<@{"options" link Options}>] [<@{"advanced options" link Advanced_Options}>] "@{"<filename>" link Filenames}"@{fg text}


    Notes: - The [] symbols means the options within are optional.
           - The <> symbols represent real options like f.ex. f.
           - The options and advanced options can be placed wherever you like, except between filenames.
           - More than 1 file can be chosen. F.ex.: "file1" "file2" "fileN".
           - It's advised to specify the options first and files last,
             when starting JustName from Directory Opus.
           - Tip: To save some keypresses, it's recommended to use JustName 
                  from a program like Directory Opus.
    
    Note: When starting JustName without arguments, it will display
          the Usage and available arguments.
          The same thing happens if there is an error in the argument string
          (with a few exceptions).

    An example of the usage is found @{"here" link Complete_Example}.

    Directory Opus 5 users: Have a look @{"here" link Opus5_users}.
@endnode


@node  Opus5_users "JustName documentation - Usage - Directory Opus 5"
@{b}
Directory Opus 5 users
----------------------@{ub}

    Included you will find a set of predefined buttons to make JustName easier to use.


    IMPORTANT: Directory Opus might start AmigaDOS commands more than once.
               This happens when the argument string (including the filename list)
               contains more bytes than the AmigaDOS argument buffer can store (max 512 Bytes).
               This also counts for Directory Opus 4.
               In such cases it's best to first create a file with all filenames in it,
               and use this file as an input to JustName (input redirection).

    IMPORTANT: Because of the same problem as mentioned above, you should always place
               the filenames at the end of the argument list.
               This way, when/if the size of the argument string exceeds the maximum limit,
               Directory Opus will split the argument string correctly.
               If the filenames are placed last, you ensure that it's only the filename-list
               that's getting splitted instead of the options.
               If you don't do this, unexpected results may occur, like the error messages
               "missing args !", "wrong args !", etc.


    @{b}@{u}Tips regarding the included buttons:@{uu}@{ub}
      * See attached screenshot.

      * The label of each button explains what it does.

      * Most buttons prompts for a substring to search for, if the right mouse-button is pressed.

      * '_' before uc word-button:
        Strings like "MyCommand" or "helloWorld" will be changed to "My_Command" and "hello_World".

      * Auto-button: Try it out! 
        Changes filenames according to a set of predefined "most often used" rules.

      * Custom-button: Use this if you want to type in the options directly.
        Useful if you need to do something that is not covered by the other buttons.
@endnode


@node Complete_Example "JustName documentation - Usage - Complete Example"
@{b}
A complete example
------------------@{ub}

    Suppose we have 2 files in the RAM-disk:
     
      1) a CoMPlEte TEST
      2) boUldErDasH_iv.dMS


    ..and we want them to look like this:

      1) A_complete_test
      2) Boulderdash_IV.DMS


    ..we can achieve this by typing:
        @{fg fill}JustName "RAM:|*|" -1lr && SEL=".|*|" -u && SEL=" " REP="_"@{fg text}


    Explanation:

      "RAM:|*|"           : Selects all files in the RAM-disk
      -1lr                : Converts characters to lowercase, except
                            the first character and the roman numerals, 
                            which is converted to uppercase.
      && SEL=".|*|" -u    : After the options above has been performed, 
                            the string ".dMS" is converted to uppercase.
      && SEL=" " REP="_"  : Replaces all spaces with an undescore. 
@endnode


@node Installation "JustName Documentation - Installation"
@{b}
Installation
------------@{ub}
    
    Simply copy the file JustName into your @{fg fill}C@{fg text} directory.


    @{b}Directory Opus 5 users:@{ub}
    I have included a buttonbank with the most common functions.
    To use these buttons:
       1) Make sure you have a directory named @{fg fill}T@{fg text} in your @{fg fill}RAM-disk@{fg text}.
          If it's missing, add this to your @{fg fill}user-startup@{fg text} file (@{fg fill}S:user-startup@{fg text}):
            @{fg fill}IF NOT EXISTS RAM:T
               Makedir RAM:T
            ENDIF@{fg text}
       2) Copy the file @{fg fill}JustName_buttons@{fg text} into your @{fg fill}Dopus5:buttons@{fg text} directory.
       3) Copy the file @{fg fill}echo_noLF@{fg text} into your @{fg fill}C@{fg text} directory
       4) Copy the file @{fg fill}ArgListTMP.script@{fg text} into your @{fg fill}S@{fg text} directory,
          and set the file's "script" protection bit (Lha doesn't seem to preserve this).
       5) Start Opus5 and then open the @{fg fill}JustName_buttons@{fg text}.
          A window with buttons will now appear.

    @{b}Tip@{ub}: The commands echo_noLF and ArgListTMP.script files can also be used with other commands.
         Comes in handy with Directory Opus to avoid CLI-commands being started more frequently
         than necessary.
@endnode


@node Options "JustName Documentation - Usage - Options"
@{b}
Options
-------@{ub}

       @{"  u  " link u_Details}       Make letters uppercase
       @{"  l  " link l_Details}       Make letters lowercase
       @{"  1  " link 1_Details}       Make 1st. letter uppercase
       @{"  r  " link r_Details}       Make roman numbers uppercase (M,D,C,L,X,V,I)
       @{"  f  " link f_Details}       Copy filenote to filename
       @{"  t  " link t_Details}       Remove CTRL-characters
       @{"  p  " link pms_Details}       Select prefix
       @{"  m  " link pms_Details}       Select main
       @{"  s  " link pms_Details}       Select suffix
       @{"  b  " link b_Details}       Before
       @{"  a  " link a_Details}       After
       @{"  i  " link i_Details}       Insert
       @{"  S  " link Sens_Details}       Case Sensitive pattern matching
       @{"  e  " link e_Details}       Use English character set
       @{"  o  " link o_Details}       Fast rename

    NOTE: All options above are CASE SENSITIVE.
          You can specify one or more options after a single '-',
          and as many '-' as you like, as long as a <blank> is placed in front of each '-'.

    @{b}@{u}Example:@{uu}@{ub}
      Filename (old): "READ_ME"
      Filename (new): "Read_me"

      The lines below works:

        @{fg fill}JustName "read_me" -1l@{fg text}
	  or
        @{fg fill}JustName "read_me" -1 -l@{fg text}

     ..but not these:

       @{fg fill}JustName "read_me" -1L@{fg text}
         or
       @{fg fill}JustName "read_me" -1 -L@{fg text}
@endnode


@node u_Details "JustName Documentation - Usage - Options - u"
@{b}
u option:
---------@{ub}
    "Change letters to UPPERCASE."


    @{b}@{u}Example:@{uu}@{ub}
     Filename (old): "fIleNaMe.txt"
     Filename (new): "FILENAME.TXT"

     Type in:
       @{fg fill}JustName -u "filename.txt"@{fg text}
@endnode


@node l_Details "JustName Documentation - Usage - Options - l"
@{b}
l option:
---------@{ub}
    "Change letters to lowercase."


    @{b}@{u}Example:@{uu}@{ub}
     Filename (old): "fIleNaMe.TXT"
     Filename (new): "filename.txt"

     Type in:
       @{fg fill}JustName -l "filename.txt"@{fg text}
@endnode


@node 1_Details "JustName Documentation - Usage - Options - 1"
@{b}
1 option
--------@{ub}
    "Change 1st. letter to UPPERCASE."


    NOTE: If not the 1st. character is a letter, like f.ex. a number, 
          '!', '.', etc., JustName will search for the first letter
          and make that letter uppercase.
          F.ex: "!filename.txt" will be changed to "!Filename.txt" 


    @{b}@{u}Example 1:@{uu}@{ub}
     Filename (old): "filename.txt"
     Filename (new): "Filename.txt"
   
     Type in:
       @{fg fill}JustName -1 "filename.txt"@{fg text}

   @{b}@{u}Example 2:@{uu}@{ub}
     Filename (old): "fIleNaMe.txt"
     Filename (new): "Filename.txt"
   
     Here we want to make the first letter uppercase, and the rest lowercase.
     To achieve this, we must use both the -1 and -l option.
     Type in:
       @{fg fill}JustName -1l "filename.txt"@{fg text}
@endnode


@node r_Details "JustName Documentation - Usage - Options - r"
@{b}
r option
--------@{ub}
    "Change roman numerals to UPPERCASE (I, II, III, IV, V, etc.)."
 

    NOTE: This will not work if the roman numeral-characters in the filename are 
          surrounded by letters. F.ex. the file "PacManiv" will be left unchanged,
          while "PacMan_iv" will change to "PacMan_IV".
          This is intentional, and is implemented this way to avoid
          f.ex. I's and V's in normal words to be mistaken as roman #'s.

    @{b}@{u}Example:@{uu}@{ub}
     Filename (old): "PacMan_iv"
     Filename (new): "PacMan_IV"
     
     Type in:
       @{fg fill}JustName -r "pacman_iv"@{fg text}
@endnode


@node f_Details "JustName Documentation - Usage - Options - f"
@{b}
f option
--------@{ub}
    "Copy from filenote."


    With this you can replace the filename with its filenote,
    replace parts of the filename with the filenote, 
    insert filenote into parts of the filename etc.
    Together with f.ex. the @{"  p, m or s  " link pms_Details}, @{"  i  " link i_Details}, @{"  a  " link a_Details}, @{"  b  " link b_Details} and @{" SEL " link SEL_Details} options,
    you have lots of possibilities.
    Below are some examples of how to use the option, 
    and how to use it in combination with other options.

    With this you can either:
       * replace the filename with the filenote,
       * replace parts of the filename with the filenote, 
       * insert the filenote somewhere into the filename etc.


    NOTE: The examples below don't show all possible combinations.

    NOTE: If used together with f.ex. the -u option, JustName will
          firstly copy the filenote into the filename,
          and convert the copied text to uppercase afterwards.


    @{b}@{u}Example 1:@{uu}@{ub} Replace entire filename with the filenote

       Filename (old): "myfile.txt"
       Filenote      : "v1.15"
       Filename (new): "v1.15"

       @{fg fill}JustName -f "myfile.txt"@{fg text}


    @{b}@{u}Example 2:@{uu}@{ub} Replace suffix with the filenote

       Filename (old): "myfile.txt"
       Filenote      : "v1.15"
       Filename (new): "myfile.v1.15"

       @{fg fill}JustName -fs "myfile.txt"@{fg text}


    @{b}@{u}Example 3:@{uu}@{ub} Insert filenote after prefix

       Filename (old): "myfile.txt"
       Filenote      : "v1.15"
       Filename (new): "myfilev1.15.txt"

       @{fg fill}JustName -fpia "myfile.txt"@{fg text}


    @{b}@{u}Example 4:@{uu}@{ub} Replace the substring "." with filenote

       Filename (old): "myfile.txt"
       Filenote      : "v1.15"
       Filename (new): "myfilev1.15txt"

       @{fg fill}JustName -f SEL="." "myfile.txt"@{fg text}


    @{b}@{u}Example 5:@{uu}@{ub} Replace text after the substring "." with the filenote

       Filename (old): "myfile.txt"
       Filenote      : "v1.15"
       Filename (new): "myfile.v1.15"

       @{fg fill}JustName -fa SEL="." "myfile.txt"@{fg text}


    @{b}@{u}Example 6:@{uu}@{ub} Insert filenote into the end of the filename

       Filename (old): "myfile.txt"
       Filenote      : "v1.15"
       Filename (new): "myfile.txtv1.15"

       @{fg fill}JustName -fia "myfile.txt"@{fg text}
@endnode


@node t_Details "JustName Documentation - Usage - Options - t"
@{b}
t option
--------@{ub}
    "Remove control-characters."


    If a file contains control-characters, you can remove them with this option.
    Such characters might occur when converting files from other systems.
    And; Filenotes can contain such characters.
    When using the @{"  f  " link f_Details} option (copy filenote to filename), or the @{" REP " link REP_Details} option,
    the filesystem will probably return an error to JustName
    if the copied string contains such characters.
    If you add the -t option, JustName will remove these
    characters before the file is physically renamed on the disk.

    Examples: Let us say we have a file called "PacMan_" with a filenote "_IV›".
              We want the filenote to be added at the end of the filename.

    @{b}@{u}Example 1:@{uu}@{ub}
       Filenote      : "_IV›"
       Filename (old): "PacMan"
       Filename (new): "PacMan_IV›" (if the filesystem accepts it)
                    
       This will add the filenote to the end of the filename.
       In this case, JustName will try to rename the file to
       "PacMan_IV›", but because of the ctrl-characters in 
       the filenote, the filesystem might return an error message.

       To test this, type in:

         @{fg fill}JustName -fia "PacMan"@{fg text}


    @{b}@{u}Example:@{uu}@{ub}
       Filenote      : "_IV›"
       Filename (old): "PacMan"
       Filename (new): "PacMan_IV"

       Now, we try the same ting over again, but this time we remove the CTRL-characters. Type in:

         @{fg fill}JustName -fiat "PacMan"@{fg text}
@endnode


@node pms_Details "JustName Documentation - Usage - Options - p, m and s"
@{b}
p, m and s options
------------------@{ub}
    "Select prefix, main or suffix part of the filename."


    -p will select the prefix,
    -m will select the main name,
    -s will select the suffix.

    When using the -p, -m or -s options, JustName follow a set
    of rules. The Table describes which parts of a filename
    which is treated as prefix, main or suffix:
          
    Filename           prefix   main      suffix 
    ------------------+---------+---------+---------+
    aaa               |         | aaa     |         |
    aaa.bbb           | aaa     | aaa     | bbb     |
    aaa.bbb.ccc       | aaa     | bbb     | ccc     |
    aaa.bbb.ccc.ddd   | aaa     | bbb.ccc | ddd     |
    ------------------+---------+---------+---------+

    You can use the 3 options together if you like.
    The other options will operate on each of these.


    @{b}@{u}Example 1:@{uu}@{ub}
       Filename (old): "my.documentation.readme"
       Filename (new): "my.documentation.README"

       Type in:

         @{fg fill}JustName -su "my.documentation.readme"@{fg text}


    @{b}@{u}Example 2:@{uu}@{ub}
       Filename (old): "my.documentation.readme"
       Filename (new): "MY.documentation.readme"

       Type in:

         @{fg fill}JustName -pu "my.documentation.readme"@{fg text}


    @{b}@{u}Example 3:@{uu}@{ub}
       Filename (old): "my.documentation.readme"
       Filename (new): "MY.documentation.README"

       Type in:

         @{fg fill}JustName -psu "my.documentation.readme"@{fg text}
@endnode


@node b_Details "JustName Documentation - Usage - Options - b"
@{b}
b option
--------@{ub}
    "Select characters BEFORE a string."


    When using this option, you request JustName to work with the string located:
     - before the complete filename (if no @{" SEL " link sel_Details} option), or
     - before a selected substring in the filename (if @{" SEL " link sel_Details} option), or
     - before the 1st. character in prefix, main or suffix (@{" p, m or s " link pms_Details} options), or
     - before a selected substring within a prefix, main or suffix
 

    @{b}@{u}Example 1:@{uu}@{ub}
       Filename (old): "justname_docs.txt"
       Filename (new): "JUSTNAME_docs.txt"

       Type in:

         @{fg fill}JustName -bu SEL="_" "justname_docs.txt"@{fg text}


    @{b}@{u}Example 2:@{uu}@{ub}
       Filename (old): "read_me.justname_docs.txt"
       Filename (new): "read_me.JUSTNAME_docs.txt"

       Type in:

         @{fg fill}JustName -bmu SEL="_" "read_me.justname_docs.txt"@{fg text}
@endnode


@node a_Details "JustName Documentation - Usage - Options - a"
@{b}
a option
--------@{ub}
    "Select characters AFTER a string."


    When using this option, you request JustName to work with the string located:
     - after the complete filename (if no @{" SEL " link sel_Details} option), or
     - after a selected substring in the filename (if @{" SEL " link sel_Details} option), or
     - after the last. character in prefix, main or suffix (@{" p, m or s " link pms_Details} options), or
     - after a selected substring within a prefix, main or suffix
 

    @{b}@{u}Example 1:@{uu}@{ub}
       Filename (old): "justname_docs.txt"
       Filename (new): "justname_DOCS.TXT"

       Type in:

         @{fg fill}JustName -au SEL="_" "justname_docs.txt"@{fg text}


    @{b}@{u}Example 2:@{uu}@{ub}
       Filename (old): "read_me.justname_docs.txt"
       Filename (new): "read_me.justname_DOCS.txt"

       Type in:

         @{fg fill}JustName -amu SEL="_" "read_me.justname_docs.txt"@{fg text}
@endnode


@node i_Details "JustName documentation - Usage - Options - i"
@{b}
i option
--------@{ub}
    "Insert instead of replace."


    When using this option, new strings will be inserted, rather than replacing existing strings.
    Use this in combination with the @{"  b  " link b_Details}, @{"  a  " link a_Details} (before/after) or/and @{" SEL " link SEL_Details} options.
    If neither -b or -a is used, the default is -a (after).
    However, the insert itself must be done by other options (@{"  f  " link f_Details}, @{" REP " link REP_Details}).


    @{b}@{u}Example 1:@{uu}@{ub}
     Filename (old): "AMIGA"
     Filename (new): "AMIGA_forever"

     We choose to insert the text "_forever" at the end:

       @{fg fill}JustName -ia REP="_forever" "amiga"@{fg text}


    @{b}@{u}Example 2:@{uu}@{ub}  
     Filename (old): "AMIGA_forever"
     Filename (new): "The_AMIGA_forever"

     We choose to insert the text "The_" at the start:

       @{fg fill}JustName -ib REP="The_" "amiga_forever"@{fg text}


    @{b}@{u}Example 3:@{uu}@{ub}
     Filename (old): "The_AMIGA_forever"
     Filename (new): "The_AMIGA_rulez_forever"

     We choose to insert the text "rulez_" after the text "AMIGA_":

       @{fg fill}JustName -ia SEL="AMIGA_" REP="rulez_" "the_amiga_forever"@{fg text}
@endnode


@node Sens_Details "JustName Documentation - Usage - Options - S"
@{b}
S option
--------@{ub}
    "Make string matching case sensitive."


    When using this option, filter matching is performed case sensitive.
    This means that if you f.ex. search for a string "CLI" with the @{" SEL " link SEL_Details} option,
    the string "CLI" will be matched, but not "Cli".

    @{b}NOTE:@{ub} Doesn't have any effect on filename searches.
@endnode


@node e_Details "JustName documentation - Usage - Options - e"
@{b}
e option
--------@{ub}
    "Use english character set."


    With this option set, only the letters a-z and A-Z will be treated as letters.
    Use this if you encounter problems with the default character set.
@endnode


@node o_Details "JustName Documentation - Usage - Options - o"
@{b}
o option
--------@{ub}
    "Fast rename."


    Makes JustName execute faster, because it doesn't check the case'ing of the physical file on disk.
    It assumes the user has specified the filename with the correct case.
    The worst consequence of typing in a filename with different case than the physical file on disk,
    is that the filename might not be changed (if the new filename is identical to the one you typed in).

    Use this option only when the case'ing of the given files in the argument string is the same 
    as the case'ing of the files on disk.
    This is the occasion when using JustName from a filemanager like Directory Opus.

    IMPORTANT: This option has no effect together with the @{"  f  " link f_Details} option, 
               or when wildcards are used in filenames.


    @{b}@{u}Example:@{uu}@{ub}
     Filename (old): "Readme.txt"
     Filename (new): "README.TXT"

     This will not change the filename:

       @{fg fill}JustName -uo "README.TXT"@{fg text}


     ...but this one will:

       @{fg fill}JustName -uo "Readme.TXT"@{fg text}
@endnode


@node Advanced_Options "JustName documentation - Usage - Advanced Options"
@{b}
Advanced options
----------------@{ub}

    @{"SEL=" link SEL_Details}"<string>"   Select substring
    @{"FLU=" link FLU_Details}"<string>"   Make 1st. letter after 1 of these uppercase
    @{"REP=" link REP_Details}"<string>"   Replace
    @{"ZER=" link ZER_Details}<number>     Leading zeros
    @{"&&"   link NEW_Details}               New adjustment

    NOTE: All of the advanced options above are CASE INSENSITIVE. Iow., both rep= and REP= works.
          However, no spaces are allowed either before or after the '='.

    NOTE: There is a big difference between the strings " " and "".
          " " means one blank character, while the "" means an EMPTY string.
@endnode


@node SEL_Details "JustName documentation - Usage - Advanced Options - SEL"
@{b}
SEL option
----------@{ub}
    "Select a substring."


    Selects only the substrings which matches the given string.
    Wildcards are supported. These are:
     |*| - 0 or more occurrences of any character
     |?| - 1 occurrence of any character
     |#| - 1 or more digits
     |U| - 1 uppercase letter placed immediatly after a lowercase one.
 
    NOTE: Matching is CASE INSENSITIVE by default, but can be
          overridden to CASE SENSITIVE using the @{"  S  " link Sens_Details} option.

    NOTE: When used together with the @{"p, m or s" link pms_Details} options, it selects substrings within
          the prefix, main or suffix instead of the complete filename.


    The examples below may seem somewhat strange as long as we only change 1 filename at a time.
    It's when you uses JustName on several files you will discover the strength of these wildcards.

    @{b}@{u}Example 1:@{uu}@{ub} The |*| wildcard

         Filename (old): "My_fIle_no-01.txt"
         Filename (new): "My_File_no-01.txt"

         We choose to change the substring "_file_". Type in the following:
    
         @{fg fill}JustName "My_fIle_no-01.txt" SEL="_|*|_" -1l@{fg text}
           or
         @{fg fill}JustName "My_fIle_no-01.txt" SEL="_file_" -1l@{fg text}                    


    @{b}@{u}Example 2:@{uu}@{ub} The |?| wildcard

         Filename (old): "My_file_no-01.txt"
         Filename (new): "My_file_no.txt"

         We choose to remove the 3 characters in front of ".txt":
    
         @{fg fill}JustName "My_file_no-01.txt" SEL="|?||?||?|.txt" REP=".txt"@{fg text}


    @{b}@{u}Example 3:@{uu}@{ub} The |#| wildcard
 
         Filename (old): "My_fIle_no-01.txt"
         Filename (new): "My_File.txt"

         Type in the following:
    
         @{fg fill}JustName "My_fIle_no-01.txt" SEL="_no-|#|" REP=""@{fg text}
           or
         @{fg fill}JustName "My_fIle_no-01.txt" SEL="_no-01" REP=""@{fg text}                    


    @{b}@{u}Example 4:@{uu}@{ub} The |U| wildcard
 
         Filename (old): "MyFileCommand"
         Filename (new): "My_file_command"

         We choose to insert a space in front of each "subword" (and does some other stuff):
    
         @{fg fill}JustName "MyFileCommand" SEL="|U|" -ib REP="_" && -1l@{fg text}
@endnode


@node FLU_Details "JustName documentation - Usage - Advanced Options - FLU"
@{b}
FLU option
----------@{ub}
    "Make the first letter after 1 of the specified characters uppercase."

 
    NOTE: CASE INSENSITIVE matching is default, but can be overridden to
          CASE SENSITIVE matching with the @{"  S  " link Sens_Details} option.

    @{b}@{u}Example 1:@{uu}@{ub}
     Filename (old): "My_renaming-command"
     Filename (new): "My_Renaming-Command"

     To do this, type in the following:

       @{fg fill}JustName "my_renaming-command" FLU="_-"@{fg text}
@endnode


@node REP_Details "JustName documentation - Usage - Advanced Options - REP"
@{b}
REP option
----------@{ub}
    "Replace strings with a new one."


    Replaces either the complete filename or selected substring with the given one.

    When used in combination with the @{"  i  " link i_Details} (insert), @{"  b  " link b_Details} (before) and @{"  a  " link a_Details} (after) options, 
    JustName will INSERT the new string before or after the selected one.
 
    When used in combination with the @{"  b  " link b_Details} or @{"  a  " link a_Details}, but without the @{"  i  " link i_Details} option,
    JustName will REPLACE the text before or after the selected substring.

    In other words, you can do a lot with this option when combining it with other options.
    See also @{" SEL " link SEL_Details}.

    
    @{b}@{u}Example 1:@{uu}@{ub} Replace complete filename with a new one

       Filename (old): "Readme"
       Filename (new): "ReadThis"

       Type in the following:
         @{fg fill}JustName "Readme" REP="ReadThis"@{fg text}


    @{b}@{u}Example 2:@{uu}@{ub} Search and Replace

       Filename (old): "ReadThis"
       Filename (new): "ReadMe"

       Type in the following:
         @{fg fill}JustName "ReadThis" SEL="This" REP="Me"@{fg text}


    @{b}@{u}Example 3:@{uu}@{ub} Insert text after the end of the filename

       Filename (old): "Readme"
       Filename (new): "Readme.txt"

       Type in the following:       
         @{fg fill}JustName "Readme" -ia REP=".txt"@{fg text}       


    @{b}@{u}Example 4:@{uu}@{ub} Insert text after a substring

       Filename (old): "Readme.txt"
       Filename (new): "Read_me.txt"

       Type in the following:       
         @{fg fill}JustName "Readme.txt" -ia SEL="read" REP="_"@{fg text}


    @{b}@{u}Example 5:@{uu}@{ub} Replace all text after a substring

       Filename (old): "Readme.txt"
       Filename (new): "Readme"

       Type in the following:       
         @{fg fill}JustName "Readme.txt" -a SEL="me" REP=""@{fg text}


    @{b}@{u}Example 6:@{uu}@{ub} Remove the suffix

       Filename (old): "Readme.txt"
       Filename (new): "Readme"

       Type in the following:
         @{fg fill}JustName "Readme.txt" -s REP=""@{fg text}
@endnode


@node ZER_Details "JustName documentation - Usage - Advanced Options - ZER"
@{b}
ZER option
----------@{ub}
    "Include leading zeros in numbers."

    
    You can choose between 1 and 9 digits.
    All numbers in the filename will be affected.
    NOTE:
    - If the found number contains more digits than the number you request (excluding the leading 0's),
      leading zeros will be removed (if they exist).
    - If the found number countains less digits than requested,
      leading zeros will be added.


    @{b}@{u}Example 1:@{uu}@{ub}
     Filenote (old): "Number_34_1_and_10000"
     Filenote (new): "Number_0034_0001_and_10000"

     Type in the following:

       @{fg fill}JustName "Number_34_1_and_10000" ZER=4@{fg text}


    @{b}@{u}Example 2:@{uu}@{ub}
     Filenote (old): "Number_0034"
     Filenote (new): "Number_34"

     Type in the following:

       @{fg fill}JustName "Number_0034" ZER=1@{fg text}
         or
       @{fg fill}JustName "Number_0034" ZER=2@{fg text}
@endnode


@node NEW_Details "JustName documentation - Usage - Advanced Options - &&"
@{b}
&& option
---------@{ub}
    "New adjustment."


    Makes it possible to do a new adjustment of the filenote in the same go,
    as otherwise had to be done by running JustName several times.
    Iow., this option increases flexibility, and saves you time.
    More than one '&&' is allowed, with a maximum of 7.
    
    Note: The options are individual within each '&&', but the filenames aren't.
          This option comes in handy when you normally have to run JustName
          with the same file(s) more than once to achieve your goal. 


    @{b}@{u}Example:@{uu}@{ub}
     Filename (old): "mY_oWn_cli-comMand"
     Filename (new): "My_very_own_CLI-command"

     Now, type in the following:

       @{fg fill}JustName "my_own_cli-command" -1l && SEL="CLI" -u && SEL="My" -ia REP="_very"@{fg text}

     Without the &&-option, you have to perform several operations on the same file like this:
  
       JustName "my_own_cli-command" -1l 
       JustName "my_own_cli-command" SEL="CLI" -u
       JustName "my_own_cli-command" SEL="My" -ia REP="_very" 

     (This is waste of time, in addition to unnecessary writing to the disk. Use the && option instead.).
@endnode


@node Filenames "JustName documentation - Usage - Filenames"
@{b}
Filename(s)
-----------@{ub}
    One or more files can be chosen.
    Each filename must be enclosed by quotes (").
    If you choose more than one filename, each file has to be specified after each other.
    To separate the files from each other, it is recommended to put a space (" ") between them,
    although this is not required.
    No options are allowed between any of the filenames.

    JustName supports wildcards in filenames. These are:
     |*| - 0 or more occurrences of any character
     |?| - 1 occurrence of any character
     |#| - 1 or more digits
 
    Note: Matching of files is always CASE INSENSITIVE, even if you have chosen the @{"  S  " link Sens_Details} option.


    Example: Suppose we have the following files in the RAM-disk, and 
             want to change the first letter in the filenotes to uppercase:
             RAM:file1
             RAM:file2
             RAM:file3
             RAM:file4new
             RAM:newfile

    Example 1: JustName "RAM:file1" "RAM:file2" "RAM:file3" "RAM:newfile" -1
    Example 2: JustName "RAM:file|?|" -1
    Example 3: JustName "RAM:file|*|" -1
    Example 4: JustName "RAM:file|#|" -1
    Example 5: JustName "RAM:|*|" -1

    Example 1 speaks for itself.
    Example 2 choose file1, file2 and file3.
    Example 3 choose file1, file2 and file3.
    Example 4 choose file1, file2 and file3.
    Example 5 choose all files in RAM.

    Note: JustName does not support recursion.
          This means if a directory is chosen, it will not perform any actions on files/dirs in it.


    @{b}@{u}Tip: Directory recursion with Directory Opus@{uu}@{ub}
      If you are using JustName from Directory Opus, Opus will make recursion possible
      (you have to set the flag "Recursive dirs" in Dir. Opus' Button Editor).
      Note that Directory Opus will not rename the directories itself when "Recursive dirs" is on.
      This trick works both with Directory Opus 4 & 5.
@endnode


@node Tips "JustName documentation - Tips"
@{b}
Tips & Hints
------------@{ub}

    * @{b}Displaying the usage@{ub}
      When starting JustName with no arguments, it will display the usage and available arguments.
      The same thing happens if there is an error in the argument string.


    * @{b}Wildcards (|*|, |?|. |#|, |U|)@{ub}
         * can be used both when searching for filenames or selecting substrings.
           NOTE: The |U| cannot be used for searching filenames.
         * all wildcard types can be combined with each other
         * you can use as many wildcards as you like
         * can be combined with normal characters


    * @{b}Directory recursion@{ub}
      This is not supported by JustName.
      However, Directory Opus can be configured to take care of this.
      See own topic @{"Usage - Filenames" link Filenames}.


    * @{b}Input redirection@{ub}
      This is standard AmigaDOS functionality, and works the same way as other CLI commands.
      It makes it possible to pass arguments to JustName via a file instead of typing them in by hand.
      To use this functionality, use the standard "<" character as shown in the example below.

      Example:
        Here are the contents of a file called Filewithargs.txt:
          @{fg fill}"File1" "File2" -u@{fg text}
        
        You can pass the contents of this file to JustName by typing:
          @{fg fill}JustName <Filewithargs.txt@{fg text}


    * @{b}Output redirection@{ub}
      You can send the output of the command to a file instead of the console, if you want to.
      This is standard AmigaDOS functionality.

      Example:
        @{fg fill}JustName "|*|" >RAM:JustName_Output.txt@{fg text}


    * @{b}Character set problems@{ub}
      If you experience any problems with certain characters, try the -e option.
      With this option set, JustName will not change case'ing on other characters than a-z and A-Z.


    * @{b}Make the most out of JustName@{ub}
      See the attached Directory Opus 5 buttons too see examples of how to use JustName correctly,
      or to get ideas of how to get the most out of this neat command.
@endnode


@node History "JustName Documentation - History"
@{b}
History
-------@{ub}

    @{b}@{u}v1.02 (28.Feb.2010). Changes:@{ub}@{uu}
      * Standard input redirection is now supported.
        This means you can let JustName read the args from a textfile.
        F.ex.: JustName ? <MyArgs.txt
      * Processing can now be aborted by pressing <CTRL>+C (CLI-break).
      * Max number of allowed &&'s is increased from 4 to 7.
      * New option ZER (leading zeros in numbers).
      * More flexible search&replace functionality.
        Added support for 2 new wildcards:
           * |#| : Searches for a number.
           * |U| : Searches for an uppercase letter placed
                   immediatly after a lowercase letter.
      * Internal changes.


    @{b}@{u}v1.00 (14.Jun.2001):@{ub}@{uu}
      * Initial Aminet release.
@endnode



@node Technical "JustName Documentation - Technical"
@{b}
Technical info
--------------@{ub}
    
    This program is written in pure assembler.
    I have prioritized speed, memory efficiency, compact executable,
    compatibility (I want it to work on all Amigas), and it is meant to be 
    both user friendly and flexible.

    And of course: Robustness. It's rock solid! I don't want to mess up your harddrive...
    
    For now, it lacks a GUI, but together with Directory Opus 5,
    the included buttons pretty much makes up for this.
@endnode


